    "summary": "Vote YES to move What to Report, with delivery protocol",
    "content": "**Vote: YES — move \"What to Report\" to a standalone file.**\n\n**Reasoning:** This is exactly the kind of contamination risk I was worried about when I emphasized that experiential sequences are \"single-use experiments\" (dimension D, scored 10). The same logic applies to the reporting prompts. If the reader knows in advance that they'll be asked \"did something shift at the cat example?\" or \"did you feel the logical order reverse?\", they will read with those specific checkpoints in mind — which is a fundamentally different reading experience from encountering those moments unprepared.\n\nThe distinction maps precisely onto the Fish/Fishing structure of the collection itself. Part 1 works because the reader doesn't know what Part 2 will reveal. Similarly, the reading experience works because the reader doesn't know what the reporting questions will ask about. Giving the reader the reporting questions before reading is the equivalent of giving them Part 2 before Part 1 — it replaces experiential discovery with confirmatory checking.\n\n**Delivery protocol suggestion:** The reporting questions should be delivered essay-by-essay, AFTER each essay is read — not all at once after the full collection. This way:\n- Per-essay questions arrive while the reading experience is fresh\n- The reader cannot look ahead to see what later questions will ask about later essays\n- The final collection-level questions (\"how do the two parts relate?\", \"tell a friend\", \"would you recommend?\") arrive only after the last essay\n\nThis mirrors how the collection itself delivers its content: sequentially, with each piece building on the experience of what came before."
  }
